angford, Suffolk, England":"Wangford, Suffolk, England","King's Lynn, Norfolk, England":"King's Lynn, Norfolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Brandon","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places called Brandon, in Durham, Norfolk, Suffolk, Warwickshire, and elsewhere. Most are named with Old English <i>brōm</i> ‘broom, gorse’ + <i>dūn</i> ‘hill’. One in Lincolnshire, however, may be named after the Brant River, on which it stands; Ekwall derives the river name from Old English <i>brant</i> ‘steep’, presumably with reference to its steep banks. This surname was known in Ireland early enough to have a Gaelicized form <i>de Breandún</i>.","Irish (Kerry): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Breandáin</b> ‘son of <i>Breandán</i>’, a rare Kerry surname from the Latinized form of the name of the local saint, Brendan (<i>Brendanus</i> from <i>Bréanainn</i>).","French: from the Old French oblique case of the personal name <i>Brando</i>, of ancient Germanic origin (see   Brand   1)."],"variants":[{"name":"Brand","meanings":["English, Scottish, North German, Scandinavian, Dutch, and French (mainly Alsace and Lorraine): from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Brando</i>, Old Norse <i>Brandr</i>, a short form of various compound names containing the element <i>brand</i> ‘sword’ (a derivative of <i>brinnan</i> ‘to flash’), of which the best known is   Hildebrand  . There is placename evidence for <i>Brant(a)</i> as an Old English personal name; however, the Middle English personal name <i>Brand</i> was probably introduced to England from Old Norse.","German: variant of   Brandt   1 and, in North America, (also) an altered form of this.","Swedish and Danish: ornamental name or nickname from <i>brand</i> ‘fire’."]},{"name":"Brandom","meanings":["English and Jewish (Sephardic): variant of   Brandon  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert Brandon was born in 1400, in King's Lynn, Norfolk, England, his father, Sir John Brandon, was 18 and his mother, Alinore Mautby, was 19. He married Ada Calthorpe after 1436, in Ludham, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1438, in North Cray, Kent, England, at the age of 38."},"et":{"1400–1438":"1400–1438","1405–1439":"1405–1439","1425–1491":"1425–1491","1382–1424":"1382–1424","1381–1424":"1381–1424","1425":"1425","1424":"1424","Aft 1436":"pärast 1436","1400":"1400","Abt 1425":"umbes 1425","1395":"1395","1382":"1382","1381":"1381","1491":"1491","1439":"1439","1438":"1438","1405":"1405",", Ludham, Norfolk, England":"Ludham, Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","North Cray, Bromley, Kent, England":"North Cray, Kent, England","Norfolk, England, United Kingdom":"Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Wangford, Suffolk, England":"Wangford, Suffolk, England","King's Lynn, Norfolk, England":"King's Lynn, Norfolk, England"},"fi":{"1400–1438":"1400–1438","1405–1439":"1405–1439","1425–1491":"1425–1491","1382–1424":"1382–1424","1381–1424":"1381–1424","1425":"1425","1424":"1424","Aft 1436":"1436 jälkeen","1400":"1400","Abt 1425":"noin 1425","1395":"1395","1382":"1382","1381":"1381","1491":"1491","1439":"1439","1438":"1438","1405":"1405",", Ludham, Norfolk, England":"Ludham, Norfolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","North Cray, Bromley, Kent, England":"North Cray, Kent, England","Norfolk, England, United Kingdom":"Norfolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England, United Kingdom":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Wangford, Suffolk, England":"Wangford, Suffolk, England","King's Lynn, Norfolk, England":"King's Lynn, Norfolk, England"},"fr":{"1400–1438":"1400–1438","1405–1439":"1405–1439","1425–1491":"1425–1491","1382–1424":"1382–1424","1381–1424":"1381–1424","1425":"1425","1424":"1424","Aft 1436":"après 1436","1400":"1400","Abt 1425":"environ 1425","1395":"1395","1382":"1382","1381":"1381","1491":"1491","1439":"1439","1438":"1438","1405":"1405",", Ludham, Norfolk, England":"Ludham, Norfolk, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","North Cray, Bromley, Kent, England":"North Cray, Kent, Angleterre","Norfolk, England, United Kingdom":"Norfolk, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","England, United Kingdom":"Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Wangford, Suffolk, England":"Wangford, Suffolk, Angleterre","King's Lynn, Norfolk, England":"King's Lynn, Norfolk, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Robert Brandon est né en 1400, à King's Lynn, Norfolk, Angleterre, son père, Sir John Brandon, avait 18 ans et sa mère, Alinore Mautby, avait 19 ans. Il a épousé Ada Calthorpe après 1436, à Ludham, Norfolk, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fils. Il est décédé en 1438, à North Cray, Kent, Angleterre, à l’âge de 38 ans."},"de":{"1400–1438":"1400–1438","1405–1439":"1405–1439","1425–1491":"1425–1491","1382–1424":"1382–1424","1381–1424":"1381–1424","1425":"1425","1424":"1424","Aft 1436":"nach 1436","1400":"1400","Abt 1425":"